        {
            "title": "Historical Evolution of Milan",
            "content": "Milan's history dates back to around 400 BC when it was founded by the Celtic Insubres. It became a significant center of the Roman Empire after being conquered in 222 BC. Known as Mediolanum, the city flourished under Roman rule and became the capital of the Western Roman Empire in 286 AD. Throughout the Middle Ages, Milan was a center of commerce and trade, which laid the foundation for its future economic prowess. The city was ruled by various powers, including the Visconti and Sforza families, who contributed to its architectural and cultural development. The Renaissance period saw Milan become a hub of art and learning, with figures like Leonardo da Vinci leaving a lasting legacy. In the 19th century, Milan played a crucial role in the Italian unification movement, known as the Risorgimento. Today, remnants of its rich history can be seen in its architecture, with landmarks such as the Gothic Cathedral of Milan (Duomo di Milano), the Sforza Castle, and the Santa Maria delle Grazie convent, which houses da Vinci's famous mural, 'The Last Supper.'",
